Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Put the sweet potato chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{2%tbsp}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml} into a medium #saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Zest and halve the @lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{2%tbsp} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the pak choi and stir-fry until just soft, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), @yellow Thai style paste{45%g} and garlic. Stir fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Once fragrant, add the @coconut milk{180%ml}, @soy sauce{15%ml} and @sugar{1%tsp} to the frying pan. Stir well to combine and bring to the boil.

Lower the heat and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the sweet potatoes are roasted, stir them through the curry along with the @peas{120%g}. Add the lime zest and a good squeeze of lime juice.

Taste the curry and add salt, pepper, sugar and more lime juice if needed.

Share the rice between your #serving bowls{}.

Spoon over the curry. Serve with any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!